description:
In db.rs, mark_notes_spent() issues one UPDATE statement per note_id:

  let mut txn = self.pool.begin().await?;
  for &note_id in note_ids {
      let result = sqlx::query("UPDATE notes SET spent = 1, spending_txid = ? WHERE note_id = ?")
          .bind(spending_txid)
          .bind(note_id)
          .execute(&mut *txn)
          .await?;
      ...
  }
  txn.commit().await?;

With N notes selected (e.g. 20 notes for a dust-consolidation transaction), this issues N sequential await points. While all are within a single SQLite transaction (so atomicity is maintained), the N round-trips to the DB are unnecessary. A single UPDATE...WHERE note_id IN (?, ?, ...) would accomplish the same result with one round-trip.

Comparison: spent_note_ids_in() already uses IN (...) correctly. mark_notes_spent() should follow the same pattern.

This is particularly relevant in the dust-attack/consolidation scenario where 50-100 small notes might be spent in a single transaction, requiring 50-100 individual awaits.
